# Yor√πb√° Universal Dependencies (UD) Treebank Annotation Guidelines  

  Version 1.0   ‚Äì Maintained by Ayodeji Olupinla  

This document outlines the annotation principles used in the Yor√πb√° UD treebank to ensure   consistency, accuracy, and compliance with UD standards  .

---

##   1. General Guidelines  
- All annotations follow   Universal Dependencies (UD) v2 guidelines  .
- The dataset represents   spoken Yor√πb√°  , sourced from   high school textbooks  .
-   Tonal distinctions   are   not explicitly marked   in UD annotation; instead,   glossing and context   are used for disambiguation.
- The annotation process was   manually reviewed   with the assistance of a degree-holding Yor√πb√° linguist,   Akinpelu Olugbenro (BA. Ed.)  .

---

##   2. Part-of-Speech (POS) Tagging Guidelines  
The following   Universal Part-of-Speech (UPOS) tags   were used in the Yor√πb√° UD treebank:

|   POS Tag   |   Example   |   Explanation   |
|------------|------------|----------------|
|   NOUN   | √¨w√© ("book") | Used for common nouns. |
|   PROPN   | √íj√≥ ("Ojo") | Used for proper names. |
|   PRON   | mo ("I") | Includes subject and object pronouns. |
|   VERB   | l·ªç ("go") | Main verbs, including serial verb constructions. |
|   AUX   | ti ("has"), y√≥√≤ ("will") | Aspect and modality markers. |
|   ADP   | s√≠ ("to"), n√≠ ("in") | Used for locative and directional relations. |
|   DET   | n√°√† ("the"), √†w·ªçn ("some") | Determiners, articles, and quantifiers. |
|   ADJ   | tuntun ("new") | Adjectives that modify nouns. |
|   ADV   | p√∫p·ªçÃÄ ("a lot"), d√°ad√°a ("well") | Adverbs, including reduplicated forms. |
|   SCONJ   | t√≠ ("that"), b√≠ ("if") | Subordinating conjunctions. |
|   CCONJ   | √†ti ("and") | Coordinating conjunctions. |
|   PART   | ni ("FOC"), k√≤ ("NEG") | Particles, including focus markers and negation. |
|   NUM   | m√©j√¨ ("two") | Numerals, cardinal and ordinal. |
|   PUNCT   | . , ? ! | All punctuation marks. |

---

##   3. Dependency Relations  
###   3.1 Root and Sentence Structure  
- Every sentence must have   a single root   assigned to the main verb.
- Nominal subjects (`nsubj`) and objects (`obj`) directly attach to the   root verb  .

  Example:    
# text = ·∫∏mi ni ·ªçm·ªç y√≠n. ("I am your child")
1	·∫∏mi	·∫πmi	PRON	_	_	3	nsubj	_	Gloss=I
2	ni	ni	AUX	_	_	3	cop	_	Gloss=am
3	·ªçm·ªç	·ªçm·ªç	NOUN	_	_	0	root	_	Gloss=child
4	y√≠n	y√≠n	PRON	_	_	3	nmod:poss	_	Gloss=your
5	.	.	PUNCT	_	_	3	punct	_	_


---

###   3.2 Serial Verb Constructions (SVCs)  
-   SVCs are annotated using `compound:svc`  .
-   Conjunctions are absent  ; all verbs   share the same subject  .
-   Each verb remains independent   (unlike auxiliary verbs).

  Example:    
# text = M√≥n√¨ s√°r√© w·ªçl√© l·ªçÃÅ gb√© √†k√†b√† j√°de.(Moni rushed inside to carry the ladder out)
1	M√≥n√¨	m√≥n√¨	PROPN	_	_	2	nsubj	_	Gloss=Moni
2	S√°r√©	s√°r√©	VERB	_	_	0	root	_	Gloss=rushed
3	W·ªçl√©	w·ªçl√©	VERB	_	_	2	compound:svc	_	Gloss=entered
4	L·ªçÃÅ	l·ªçÃÅ	VERB	_	_	2	compound:svc	_	Gloss=went
5	Gb√©	gb√©	VERB	_	_	2	compound:svc	_	Gloss=carried
6	√Äk√†b√†	√†k√†b√†	NOUN	_	_	5	obj	_	Gloss=ladder
7	J√°de	j√°de	VERB	_	_	2	compound:svc	_	Gloss=out
8	.	.	PUNCT	_	_	2	punct	_	_


---

###   3.3 Aspect and Mood Markers  
-   Aspect markers (`ti`, `nÃÅ`, `y√≥√≤`)   are tagged as `AUX` and linked to the verb with `aux`.

  Example:    
J√≠d√© m√°a ≈Ñ l·ªç s√≠ √àk√≥ n√≠ √≤·π£√≤√≤s√π. (Jide always goes to Lagos every month)
1	J√≠d√©	j√≠d√©	PROPN	_	_	4	nsubj	_	Gloss=Jide
2	m√°a	m√°a	AUX	_	_	4	aux	_	Gloss=habitually
3	nÃÅ	nÃÅ	AUX	_	_	4	aux	_	Gloss=is
4	l·ªç	l·ªç	VERB	_	_	0	root	_	Gloss=goes
5	s√≠	s√≠	ADP	_	_	6	case	_	Gloss=to
6	√àk√≥	√®k√≥	PROPN	_	_	4	obl	_	Gloss=Lagos
7	n√≠	n√≠	ADP	_	_	8	case	_	Gloss=every
8	√≤·π£√≤√≤s√π	√≤·π£√≤√≤s√π	NOUN	_	_	4	obl	_	Gloss=monthly
7	.	.	PUNCT	_	_	4	punct	_	_


---

###   3.4 Adpositions (`ADP`)  
-   Locative and directional words (`n√≠`, `s√≠`) are ADP  .
- The noun that follows is labeled `obl`.

  Example:    
 text = Od√πduw√† t√©d√≤ s√≠ Il√©-If·∫πÃÄ.(Oduduwa settled in Ile-Ife)
1	Od√πduw√†	od√πduw√†	PROPN	_	_	2	nsubj	_	Gloss=Oduduwa
2	t√©d√≤	t√©d√≤	VERB	_	_	0	root	_	Gloss=founded.settlement
3	s√≠	s√≠	ADP	_	_	4	case	_	Gloss=in
4	Il√©-If·∫πÃÄ	il√©-if·∫πÃÄ	PROPN	_	_	2	obl	_	Gloss=Ile-Ife
5	.	.	PUNCT	_	_	2	punct	_	_


---

###   3.5 Negation (`PART`)  
- The negation marker `k√≤` is   labeled PART   and attached to the verb with `advmod`.

  Example:    
# text = A·π£·ªç d√∫d√∫ k√≤ d√°ra. (Black CLothes are not good)
1	A·π£·ªç	a·π£·ªç	NOUN	_	_	4	nsubj	_	Gloss=cloth
2	D√∫d√∫	d√∫d√∫	ADJ	_	_	1	amod	_	Gloss=black
3	K√≤	k√≤	PART	_	_	4	neg	_	Gloss=not
4	D√°ra	d√°ra	VERB	_	_	0	root	_	Gloss=is good
5	.	.	PUNCT	_	_	4	punct	_	_


